<subSubSection id="5A9465406E5B3F194044F9EFFEFB9104" pageId="15" pageNumber="104" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="123136CB6E5B3F194044F9EFFEFB9104" blockId="15.[270,1103,1199,1620]" pageId="15" pageNumber="104">
<emphasis id="20FAEAD96E5B3F194044F9EFFE3C914E" bold="true" box="[296,423,1545,1566]" pageId="15" pageNumber="104">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name, 
<emphasis id="20FAEAD96E5B3F194345F9ECFDF8914F" box="[553,611,1546,1567]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="104">
<taxonomicName id="D58E4D486E5B3F194345F9ECFDFB914F" authorityName="Erwin" authorityYear="2000" box="[553,608,1546,1567]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Agra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="104" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aeris">aeris</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
is from the Latin meaning ‘‘of the air’’ referring the fact that these beetles live in the high frontier of the tropical forest canopy.
</paragraph>
